By now you should have received a mailing that included our calendar and bell schedule. Here are a few clarifications that we would like to point out:

1. School will dismiss early on Fridays at 1:50pm. (Unless it is scheduled as a half day on the calendar.)

2. The regular school day Monday through Thursday will go from 8:00am to 3:00pm.

3. All scheduled half days will run from 8:00am to 11:20am.

Please be sure you are aware of these changes and please share this post to help us spread the word.

post_text:
Today a committee of staff, administration, and a board member had a Return to School Planning Session to work on our COVID-19 Preparedness and Response Plan. Basic guidelines were discussed to be compliant with the MI Safe Schools 2020-2021 Return to School Roadmap but more specific details on day to day processes will be planned out with subcommittees over the next few weeks. These details will then need to be approved by the School Board and Huron ISD. Upon approval, they will be made available on our website seven days prior to the start date of school or August 17, whichever comes first. We will also be looking for parent input in a survey we hope to release by Friday. Please be on the lookout for this survey, your input is important to us as we plan ahead.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we work together to ensure a plan is set in place that works best for all involved. If you have questions or concerns in the meantime, administration is available via phone call to meet your needs.

Thank you and GO EAGLES!

post_text:
The Summer EBT for Children (SEBTC) program will be providing free, healthy groceries to students eligible for free and reduced-price school meals this summer. Eligible students in our district will receive an SEBTC card pre-loaded with $30 worth of nutritious foods per summer month (June, July and August). Healthy foods such as milk, eggs, fresh fruits and vegetables are included in the food package. Families can use the SEBTC card in any WIC authorized store across Michigan.
SEBTC is a program of the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services, Women, Infants and Children (WIC) program, in collaboration with Michigan Department of Education. SEBTC has been funded by the USDA. For more information about which districts have been chosen or the program, visit www.sebtc-mi.com.

Due to the uncertainty over COVID-19 and the Governorâ€™s executive order closing all school buildings for the remainder of the academic year we have had to make the difficult decision to cancel the Caseville Bandâ€™s Little Cesarâ€™s Pizza Kit Fundraiser in order to assure the safety of our students and their families. We are currently working on solutions for how we will be refunding money in a manner that assures the safety of our community members as well as our staff. If you paid for your order by check, those checks have not been deposited and will not be cashed. Please make a note of this for your personal records. If you paid by cash, we ask for your patience as we try to determine the safest and most efficient way to return your money. Thank you for your support. Please be safe and stay healthy!

post_text:
Good Morning from Miss S! Life In quarantine has been tricky for myself & my family. We have been surviving though. It is amazing what being stuck at your house can do for the kids! The kids have built a fort in our very small woods area. We have put a 2000 piece Disney puzzle together & colored. My kids have learned how to play a golf card game, yahtzee, pictionary air & lots more. It has been a much needed bonding time so far. Of course we have been doing school work & practicing for the upcoming baseball/softball seasons!

I miss all your smiling faces! I hope through this time of being limited, you all use your imaginations while playing, are being respectful to your parents & siblings. Helping around the house & keeping your brains moving!

GO EAGLES!

We are proud to announce the Class of 2020 valedictorian and salutatorian. Our valedictorian is Rayne Avalos. Our salutatorian is Bayley McIlhargie.

Rayne is the daughter of Candice Avalos of Pigeon. In the fall, she will be attending Michigan Technological University where she plans to pursue a degree in biomedical engineering.

Bayley is the daughter of Dan and Tonya McIlhargie of Caseville. In the fall, she will be attending Ferris State University to study pre-dentistry.

Again, thank you.

Caseville Community Food Pantry
March 16 at 3:32 PM Â·

In light of the recent developments regarding the Corona virus or COVID 19 and Governor Whitmer issueing a State of Emergency for the State of Michigan, we want to assure all of our clients that we intend to operate as usual until circumstances force a change.

We are working closely with Caseville Public School to bring in those families that need food and meal assistance while school is closed as well as acquiring food from them that would otherwise go unused.

Delivery service can be arranged for those who are home bound or do not have transportation to the pantry.

As a reminder, we serve residents of Caseville, Caseville Township and Lake Township. Proof of residency in the form of a Driver's License or State issued ID is required as well as information regarding family income.

We are working on contingency plans if we can not serve clients face to face as we have been doing. We will be sure to keep everyone posted of any changes as soon as we can.

Thank you for constant support and may this crisis pass us with little or no effect. ğŸŒº

Just a few weeks ago, we would never have anticipated that the governor would mandate school closures across our state. But here we are on March 16, 2020, and so many of our amazing families are stepping up to this new challenge. We want you to know that we are here to support you, provide resources, and grow along the way with you. Please be sure to check back daily as we share resources and learning tips on this page and please send us photos of your child learning at home to share! Comment below on how day one is going so far for you!

Caseville Public School has donated all perishables to local daycare businesses equally which included dairy and produce. We are working closely with the Caseville Community Food Pantry with all of our other food on hand as well to ensure our families in need still have food.

Caseville Community Food Pantry will be open this Friday from 12-3pm as regularly scheduled. The Caseville Community Food Pantry is located in the Helping Hands Thrift Shop on Main Street. The pantry serves individuals and families in need who live in Caseville, Caseville Township or Lake Township. The pantry is open every Friday, except holidays, from noon until 3:00 p.m.

Between the school and the pantry, there is plenty of food available. Please consider stopping by to stock up for your family and please share!

This two-time TonyÂ® and Drama Desk Award-winning treat is packed with nonstop laughs, over 150 zany characters (played by a ridiculously talented cast of 10), an onstage plane crash, villains, Scottish accents, and some good old-fashioned romance! NOTICE OF BOARD VACANCY

If the majority of the Board is still seated, the vacancy shall be filled by the Board using the following procedure:

A. The Board shall seek qualified and interested candidates from the community through the media, word of mouth, and or contacts with appropriate organizations.

B. All applicants are to submit a notice of their interest, in writing, to the Board President.

C. Appointment by the Board to fill vacancy shall be by majority vote of the full Board.

It was a great way to celebrate how far they've come and how much they've learned in 100 days.

Our middle and high school Robotics Teams performed well at the Regional Robotics Competition Saturday! Here are some highlights!

1. The high school had a team comprised of Katie McCormick, Pinkney Barrios, Lyssa Tucker and Julias Errer that made it to finals!

2. The middle school teams brought home two trophies!

* The Judges Award was earned by Grace Wilton, Michael Norkiewicz, Nathan Diehl, Maleighya Thompson and Nathan Burns.

*The highest honor of the day, the Excellence Award was given to the best all-around team, Samantha Harder and Kaila Love! Sam and Kaila will be competing a the state level March 1st!

The trophies will be displayed in the office, Congratulations to all!

post_text:
To honor the life of Mrs. Janet Watts and her dedication to Caseville Public School, we will not have school this Friday, January 31. Mrs. Watts worked 42 years in education, as a teacher, counselor, and elementary principal, and retired from Caseville Public School. She had a strong passion for our students and staff and didn't hesitate to serve them in any way she was able. She will be greatly missed.

Funeral services will be held at 11:00am on Friday, January 31st, here at our school auditorium with Rev. Karen Bouverette officiating. Burial will be in Caseville Twp Cemetery. A Celebration of Life luncheon will follow the service at Seasons Change Home Health 8201 Port Austin Rd, Pigeon.

The Coming Home Game against CPS and festivities will still be held Friday evening and we encourage all to attend.

Please share, thank you.

PLEASE READ, WE NEED YOUR HELP!

We are excited to announce that we will now be "Honoring a Veteran" at each home game this winter.

In order to do this, we need your help! In the comments below, or through messenger, please nominate a Veteran you feel should be honored at a home game and why.

We will reach out to each and invite one or more to our home games. They will receive free admission, a free water and hot dog at concessions and will be honored prior to the National Anthem.

We are so proud of the brave men and women who have served our Country and are so excited to introduce them to our fans at sporting events!

Please share and of course GO EAGLES!

The fourth graders were working to create simple electrical circuits today. The Sun was only cooperating occasionally, but the students found other sources of energy to power their fan motors. They explored ways to decrease and increase the fan speeds, as well as reversing the motor. They are really enjoying the new Amplify science curriculum.
